Place the flat side of a large #knife on top of each @garlic clove{2} and press down
firmly, the skin will come off easily. Chop them up really finely. Next, peel and
dice the @onion{1/2}(diced) and the @celery stick{1/2}(diced) as small as possible
before separating the @thyme{3%sprigs} leaves from the stalk.

Put the @vegetable stock pot{1} into a #pan with @water{800%ml}. Bring this to a
simmer before leaving it on the lowest heat possible to keep it warm. We'll add
this into the risotto bit-by-bit later on.

On a medium-low heat gently fry the @wild mushrooms{1} with 1 tsp of @olive oil{1%tsp} and
half your @Netherend butter salted{3/4}(divided) in a #non-stick pan. Add the
garlic 2 mins later, followed by the thyme leaves and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and
@pepper{pinch}. Cook for ~{2%minutes} more then set them aside on a #plate.

In the same pan on a medium-low heat, add the onion and celery to 1 tbsp of @olive oil{1%tbsp}
and the other half of your butter. After ~{5%minutes} the ingredients should be
soft (not browned off though!). Add the @risotto rice{1} with a pinch of salt and
pepper.

After a few mins you can add 1/2 cup of @?white wine{1/2%cup} if you have some.
Bubble away the alcohol for about ~{30%seconds}. If you don't have any wine just
skip straight to step 6.

Add 1/2 cup of your stock and the @fresh peas{1/3}(frozen) into the rice. While
keeping on a low heat, stir it with long, massaging motions using a #wooden spoon,
until the stock has almost disappeared. Repeat this process until all the stock
has been used (which should take around ~{20%minutes}).

Taste the rice (be careful it's hot!). It should be soft yet with a slight firmness
in the centre. If not, add 1/2 cup of @water{1/2%cup} and cook it for a little longer.
Gently mix in the cooked mushrooms and three quarters of the @grated hard Italian style cheese{1.5}.

Taste once more for seasoning and add a little salt and pepper if necessary. Serve
in #bowls with a sprinkle of the remaining cheese and if you have some good quality
@?olive oil{}, (or decadent @?truffle oil{}!) drizzle a little on top.